<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most People Get Wrong</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Buying generic tool sets.</strong> Most gardeners already have the basics, and lower-quality duplicates rarely get used.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Choosing decorative or novelty items.</strong> These can be fun, but they usually don’t improve how the garden actually performs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Ignoring timing.</strong> Spring gifts should match what gardeners are doing right now — planting, starting seeds, and dealing with weather.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most People Should Actually Gift</h2>

  <p>
    Start with high-quality seeds or simple frost protection. These are the gifts most likely to be used immediately and to improve how the season starts.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best spring gifts help the garden, not the storage shelf.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best practical gardening gifts for spring planting are the ones that support real decisions and real work — planting, protecting, and planning.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    If it gets used this week, it’s a good gift.
  </p>
